<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-114411">
<div id="div-comment-114411">
	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
		<div class="avatar"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/556f94f3791d8ea02adb7baa7eca92a4?s=32&amp;d=retro' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' /></div>		<span class="comment-author vcard"><strong class="fn">Stan Focht</strong>, on <a href="#comment-114411" title="">14 March 2011 at 2:21 AM</a> said:		</span>
			</div>

	<p>&#8220;The Zircaloy casing is the first containment.&#8221;</p>
<p>** Not Correct **</p>
<p>1st containment is the ceramic fuel pellet itself.  The fission process produces fission fragments, or radionuclides, which almost entirely remain within the ceramic fuel pellets.  Only a very small fraction of fission fragments escape the fuel pellet, unless the pelet integrity is comprimised by melting or some other degredation.</p>
<p>The 2nd barrier is the zircalloy tube; 3rd &#8211; primary coolant system; and so on&#8230;</p>
<p>This is not quibbling, but rather an important and fundemental reactor design safety feature.</p>

	<div class="reply">
			</div>
</div>
</li>

