<li class="comment byuser comment-author-bravenewclimate bypostauthor even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-114528">
<div id="div-comment-114528">
	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
		<div class="avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/66d42919adcf3f34221f7a7c94745cfe?s=32&amp;d=retro' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' /></div>		<span class="comment-author vcard"><strong class="fn"><a href='http://bravenewclimate.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Barry Brook</a></strong>, on <a href="#comment-114528" title="">14 March 2011 at 9:21 AM</a> said:		</span>
			</div>

	<p>Bill Brown, hard to say at such energy levels, but it was telling that the critical damage was done by the tsunami, knocking out all of the backup generators and redundant generators in one fell swoop. The earthquake itself simply caused a SCRAM and doesn&#8217;t seem to have damaged the reactors, which have some degree of seismic isolation. So an ocean-based incident may have made matters worse. But the time for such analysis will have to wait, too much speculation at this stage.</p>

	<div class="reply">
			</div>
</div>
</li>

