<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-114574">
<div id="div-comment-114574">
	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
		<div class="avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/a6364d315122a07083af9e093d0d5ea7?s=32&amp;d=retro' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' /></div>		<span class="comment-author vcard"><strong class="fn">David B. Benson</strong>, on <a href="#comment-114574" title="">14 March 2011 at 11:14 AM</a> said:		</span>
			</div>

	<p>Correcting a numerical error in my comment of 14 March 2011 at 10:30 AM, the increase in moment magnitude of 0.7 means 11.3 times as much energy was released as in the design basis.  If the earthquake were actually moment magnitude 9.0 [as seems likely], then the increase in moment magnitude of 0.8 means 16 times as muich energy.</p>
<p>Nonetheless, until the distance from epicenter is figured in, these calculations say little about the accelerations experienced by the nuclear power plants versus the design basis accelerations.</p>

	<div class="reply">
			</div>
</div>
</li>

