			</div>

	<p>Your synopsis implies that the pumping of sea water into the cores has cooled them.  This isn&#8217;t precisely the case.  The pressure inside the chamber is so great that they are having a hard time getting the water in with the firefighting equipment (yes, fire hoses) they&#8217;re using.  On top of that, their instruments are likely not giving accurate readings, so they&#8217;re working somewhat blind.  While they are able to keep the reactor from going into total meltdown, they aren&#8217;t able to get it sufficiently cooled to have it &#8220;off&#8221;.</p>

