<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-114988">
<div id="div-comment-114988">
	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
		<div class="avatar"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/d00dfaf81b983cab3273d8c5440213b7?s=32&amp;d=retro' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' /></div>		<span class="comment-author vcard"><strong class="fn">Dan Meneley</strong>, on <a href="#comment-114988" title="">15 March 2011 at 12:17 AM</a> said:		</span>
			</div>

	<p>Once again &#8220;m&#8221; has it wrong. The Japanese responders are doing just fine, thank you. They are doing the right things.</p>
<p>And reactor heat production is NOT increasing. Read the recent statement by the Japanese Atomic Industrial Forum. Good news all around &#8212; and true.</p>
<p>Every time the pressure of the primary containment is relieved we can expect a hydrogen explosion. Even at atmospheric  pressure, hydrogen is combustible above about 4 percent concentration. The secondary containment atmosphere is air, after all, especially after the roof has been blown off.</p>

	<div class="reply">
			</div>
</div>
