	<p>Everyone with political or economic decision making power regarding nuclear plants, should be required to put a significant amount of their personal fortune into local real estate.</p>
<p>Here is important info on the Mark I from GE that was noted for its &#8220;cost-saving&#8221; inadequacies compared to competitors 40 years ago:</p>
<blockquote><p>However, as early as 1972, Dr. Stephen Hanuaer, an Atomic Energy Commission safety official, recommended that the pressure suppression system be discontinued and any further designs not be accepted for construction permits. Shortly thereafter, three General Electric nuclear engineers publicly resigned their prestigious positions citing dangerous shortcomings in the GE design.</p>
<p>An NRC analysis of the potential failure of the Mark I under accident conditions concluded in a 1985 report that Mark I failure within the first few hours following core melt would appear rather likely.&#8221;</p></blockquote>

