<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-115052">
<div id="div-comment-115052">
	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
		<div class="avatar"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/5f1659b1e12b9feb185e67c2ecac2242?s=32&amp;d=retro' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' /></div>		<span class="comment-author vcard"><strong class="fn">Mark</strong>, on <a href="#comment-115052" title="">15 March 2011 at 1:31 AM</a> said:		</span>
			</div>

	<p>I think the big problem here was the following:  The Fukushima plant uses seawater drawn in to condense the steam after it exits the power turbines.  You can look at Google Maps and see the seawater inlets behind the seawall, and see the seawater outlet as well.  This is a normal method for cooling a power plant.</p>
<p>When the tsunami hit, it likely dredged up massive amounts of silt (just look at the after photos of all of the mud and silt in the towns), overflowed the seawall, and deposited that silt into the seawater inlets, clogging them.</p>
<p>So even with backup power, seawater could not be drawn in to condense the steam back to liquid water.</p>

	<div class="reply">
			</div>
</div>
</li>

