<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-115140">
<div id="div-comment-115140">
	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
		<div class="avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/0b130f9656c6f5a915002e69b6479b0c?s=32&amp;d=retro' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' /></div>		<span class="comment-author vcard"><strong class="fn">Juha</strong>, on <a href="#comment-115140" title="">15 March 2011 at 3:38 AM</a> said:		</span>
			</div>

	<p>Lisa, continued criticality is impossible even if control rods were not inserted, due to the boric acid in the coolant water. And since these are water moderated reactors, criticality is ALSO impossible if they dry out and there is no water at all. </p>
<p>The only time a reactor design like this can be critical is when control rods are out, AND it&#8217;s swimming in water that hasn&#8217;t been treated with neutron poison.</p>

	<div class="reply">
			</div>
</div>
</li>

<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-115146">
<div id="div-comment-115146">
