<li class="pingback even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-116131">
<div id="div-comment-116131">
	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
		<div class="avatar"></div>		<span class="comment-author vcard"><strong class="fn"><a href='http://nipon.paparaka.com/?p=136' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Fukushima Nuclear Power Plant &#8211; What You Must Know About Radiation | Ivan &amp; The Japanese People</a></strong>, on <a href="#comment-116131" title="">16 March 2011 at 3:29 AM</a> said:		</span>
			</div>

	<p>[...] The reactors in Fukushima are of the second most popular type in the world: Boiling Water Reactor. You must understand that there is no more Nuclear Chain Reaction taking place inside the reactors. However a nuclear reactor is not an electric appliance that you can just unplug. After the chain reaction stops, some elements inside the reactor start decaying, some decay fast (like seconds), others &#8211; slower. It is important to note that many of these fission products produce heat while decaying. This means that gradually they will cool down after the stop decaying. For more information on reactor physics, read here. [...]</p>

	<div class="reply">
			</div>
