<li class="comment byuser comment-author-steviesmyths even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-119297">
<div id="div-comment-119297">
	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
		<div class="avatar"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/b37cabf223f50138f2f778864619976e?s=32&amp;d=retro' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' /></div>		<span class="comment-author vcard"><strong class="fn"><a href='http://steviesmyths.wordpress.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>steviesmyths</a></strong>, on <a href="#comment-119297" title="">21 March 2011 at 9:16 AM</a> said:		</span>
			</div>

	<p>Guillaume. I highly doubt there is going to be a single catastrophic event at these reactors. It is not outside the range of possibilities, but design features of this reactor system basically prohibit massive core meltdown, because loss of coolant, is also the loss of the &#8220;moderator&#8221; that triggers reactivity.</p>
<p>The long term problem here, to my mind, is the measures that are undertaken to control that process will require ongoing releases of radiation, over a long period of time, due to the loss of the outer containment, and other factors. </p>
<p>It might take months or even years to bring the situation under full control, and in that intervening time engineers may have to make multiple controlled releases of radioactive material into the atmosphere.</p>

	<div class="reply">
			</div>
</div>
</li>

